<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="s_pells_eqn" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Pell's equations</title>
<subsection xml:id="ss_pells_eqn">
<title>Pell's equations</title>


    <definition xml:id="d_pell_eqn">
    <title>Pell's equations</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>d</m> be a positive integer that is not a square. The equation 
    <md>
        x^2-dy^2=1
    </md>
    is called <term>Pell's equation</term>. A <term>generalized Pell equation</term> is any equation of the form 
    <md>
        x^2-dy^2=n
    </md>
    where <m>n</m> is a nonzero integer. The <term>negative Pell equation</term> is the equation 
    <md>
        x^2-dy^2=-1
    </md>.
    </p>
    </statement>
    </definition>
    <theorem xml:id="th_dirichlet_approx">
    <title>Dirichlet's approximation theorem</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>\alpha</m> be an irrational real number. There are infinitely many integer pairs <m>(m,n)</m> satisfying <m>\gcd(m,n)=1</m>,  <m>n\gt; 0</m>, and 
    <md>
        \abs{n\alpha-m}&lt; \frac{1}{n}
    </md>.
    </p>
    </statement>
    <proof>
    <p>
        Fix a positive integer <m>N</m> and partition the interval <m>[0,1)</m> into the <m>n</m> disjoint subintervals 
        <md>
            I_k=[(k-1)/N, k/N)
        </md>,
        where <m>1\leq k\leq N</m>. For each <m>k\in \in \{0,1,\dots, N\}</m>, write 
        <md>
            k\alpha=\floor{k\alpha}+\beta_k, \ \beta_k=k\alpha-\floor{\alpha}
        </md>.
        Note that since <m>\alpha</m> is irrational, the <m>\beta_i</m> are themselves irrational (with the exception of <m>\beta_0=0</m>), are distinct, and satisfy <m>0&lt; \beta_k &lt; 1</m>. It follows that each <m>\beta_i</m> lies in exactly one of the intervals <m>I_k</m>, and furthermore, since there are <m>N</m> intervals <m>I_k</m> and <m>N+1</m> distinct elements <m>\beta_i</m>, by the Pigeonhole principle, there are integers <m>0\leq i&lt; j \leq n</m>, such that <m>\beta_i,\beta_j\in I_k</m> for some <m>k</m>. But then we have 
        <md>
            <mrow>\frac{1}{N} \amp &gt; \abs{\beta_j-\beta_i}</mrow>
            <mrow> \amp = \abs{(j-i)\alpha- (\floor{j\alpha}-\floor{i\alpha})}</mrow>
            <mrow> \amp = \abs{n\alpha-m}</mrow>
        </md>,
        where 
        <md>
            <mrow>n \amp =j-i\leq N \amp m= \floor{j\alpha}-\floor{i\alpha}</mrow>
        </md>,
        in which case 
        <md>
            \abs{n\alpha-m} &lt; \frac{1}{N}\leq \frac{1}{n}
        </md>.
        Moreover, letting <m>d=gcd(m,n)</m>, we have 
        <md>
            \abs{(n/d)\alpha-(m/d)}&lt; \frac{1}{dN}\leq \frac{1}{N}\leq  \frac{1}{n}\leq \frac{1}{(n/d)}
        </md>.
        Replacing <m>m</m> and <m>n</m> with  <m>m/d</m> and <m>n/d</m>, we have shown that for any positive integer <m>N</m>, we can  find a pair of relatively prime integers <m>m</m> and <m>n</m> with <m>n&gt; 0</m> satisfying <m>\abs{n\alpha-m}&lt; \frac{1}{N}\leq \frac{1}{n}</m>. To create an infinite sequence <m>(m_k,n_k)</m> of such pairs proceed recursively as follows: 
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Pick any postive <m>N_1</m>, and let <m>(m_1,n_1)</m> satisfy <m>0&lt; \abs{n_1\alpha-m_1}&lt; \frac{1}{N_1}\leq \frac{1}{n_1}</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Given pair <m>(m_k,n_k)</m>, pick any positive integer <m>N_{k+1}\geq N_K</m> satisfying <m>\frac{1}{N_{k+1}}&lt; \abs{n_k\alpha-m_k}</m>, and pick <m>(m_{k+1}, n_{k+1})</m> satisfying <m>\abs{n_{k+1}\alpha-m_{k+1}}&lt; \frac{1}{N_{k+1}}\leq \frac{1}{n_{k+1}}</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
        For any <m>k\geq 2</m>, we have 
        <md>
            <mrow>\frac{1}{N_{k+1}} \amp &lt; \abs{n_k\alpha-m_k}&lt; \frac{1}{N_{k}}</mrow>
        </md>,
        from whence it follows that pairs <m>(m_k,n_k)</m> are distinct.
    </p>
    </proof>
    </theorem>
    <theorem xml:id="th_pells_equation">
    <title>Pell's equation</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>d</m> be a positive integer that is not a square. There is a solution to the equation 
    <md>
        x^2-dy^2=1
    </md>
    in positive integers.
    </p>
    </statement>
    <proof>
    <p>
        Let <m>X</m> be the set of all pairs <m>(m,n)</m> satisfying  
        <md>
            \abs{m-n\sqrt{d}}=\abs{n\sqrt{d}-m}&lt; \frac{1}{n}
        </md>
        The set <m>X</m> is infinite by <xref ref="th_dirichlet_approx"/>. The proof will proceed in a number of steps.
        <ol>
            <li>
                <p>
                    We show that there is a nonzero integer <m>M</m> such that <m>m^2-n^2d=M</m> for infinitely many pairs <m>(m,n)\in X</m>. 
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    We show that there is an infinite subset <m>Y</m> of <m>X</m> satisfying the following properties: 
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>m^2-n^2d=1</m> for all <m>(m,n)\in Y</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                If <m>(m,n), (m',n')\in Y</m>, then <m>m\equiv m'\pmod \abs{M}</m> and <m>n\equiv n'\pmod \abs{M}</m>. 
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Associating to pairs <m>(m,n)\in Y</m> the element <m>m+n\sqrt{d}</m>, we will do some algebra in <m>\Q(\sqrt{d})</m> to construct an element <m>u=a+b\sqrt{d}\ne \pm 1</m> satisfying <m>a^2-b^2d=1</m>. 
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </p>
    <case>
    <title>Step 1</title>
    <p>
    For all <m>(m,n)\in X</m>, we have 
    <md>
        <mrow>\abs{m^2-n^2d} \amp =\abs{m+n\sqrt{d}}\abs{m-n\sqrt{d}}</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp =\abs{(m-n\sqrt{d})+2n\sqrt{d}}\abs{m-n\sqrt{d}}</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp &lt; (\abs{m-n\sqrt{d}}+\abs{2n\sqrt{d}})\cdot \frac{1}{n}</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp &lt; (\frac{1}{n}+2\sqrt{d})\cdot \frac{1}{n} </mrow>
        <mrow> \amp &lt; 1+2\sqrt{d}</mrow>
    </md>.
    Since <m>m^2-n^d\in \Z</m> for all <m>(m,n)\in X</m>, it follows that <m>m^2-n^2d</m> assumes finitely many values as <m>(m,n)</m> ranges over <m>X</m>. Since <m>X</m> is infinite, there is one value <m>M\in \Z</m> such that <m>m^2-n^2d=M</m> for infinitely-many elements of <m>X</m>. Since <m>\sqrt{d}</m> is irrational, it follows that <m>M\ne 0</m>.  
    </p>
    </case>
    <case>
    <title>Step 2</title>
    <p>
    Let <m>X'</m> be the set of all <m>(m,n)</m> satisfying <m>m^2-n^2d=M</m>, and consider the map 
    <md>
        <mrow> X'\amp \rightarrow \{0,1,\dots, \abs{M}-1\}\times \{0,1,\dots, \abs{M}-1\} \amp </mrow>
        <mrow>(m,n) \amp \mapsto (m\boldmod \abs{M}, n\boldmod \abs{M}) \amp </mrow>
    </md>
    Since <m>X'</m> is infinite and the set of pairs <m>(a,b)</m> with <m>a,b\in \{0,1,\dots, \abs{M}-1\}</m> is finite, there must be infinitely many pairs <m>(m,n)\in X'</m> that get set sent to the same pair <m>(a,b)\in \{0,1,\dots, \abs{M}-1\}\times \{0,1,\dots, \abs{M}-1\}</m>. Let <m>Y</m> be the set of all such pairs <m>(m,n)\in X'</m>. Any pair <m>(m,n)</m> in <m>Y</m> satisfies <m>m^2-n^2d=M</m>, and any two pairs in <m>(m,n),(m',n')\in Y</m> satisfy 
    <md>
        <mrow>m \amp \equiv m'\equiv a</mrow>
        <mrow>n \amp\equiv n'\equiv b </mrow>
    </md>.
    </p>
    </case>
    <case>
    <title>Step 3</title>
    <p>
    Since <m>Y</m> is infinite, we can find pairs <m>(m,n)</m> and <m>(m',n')</m> satisfying <m>m^2-n^2d=(m')^2-(n')^2d=M</m> and <m>m\ne \pm m'</m>, <m>n\ne \pm n'</m>. Let <m>K=\Q(\sqrt{d})</m> and consider the elements <m>\alpha=m+n\sqrt{d}</m>, <m>\beta=m'-n'\sqrt{d}</m> of <m>\mathcal{O}_K</m>. We have 
    <md>
        \alpha\beta=(mm'-nn'd)+(m'n-mn')\sqrt{d}
    </md>.
    Since 
    <md>
        <mrow>mm'-nn'd \amp \equiv m^2-n^2d= M \equiv 0\pmod \abs{M}</mrow>
        <mrow>m'n-mn' \amp \equiv mn-mn \equiv 0 \pmod \abs{M}</mrow>
    </md>,
    we see that <m>M\mid \alpha\beta</m>, and thus we have 
    <md>
        \alpha\beta=Mu
    </md>
    for some <m>u\in \mathcal{O}_K</m>. Now take norms of both sides and simplify: 
    <md>
        <mrow>N_K(\alpha)N_K(\beta) \amp = N_K(M)N_K(u)</mrow>
        <mrow>M\cdot M \amp = M^2N_K(u)</mrow>
        <mrow>1 \amp =N_K(u) \amp (M\ne 0)</mrow>
    </md>.
    We conclude that <m>u=a+b\sqrt{d}</m> satisfies <m>a^2-b^2d=1</m>, and is thus a solution to Pell's equation. It remains only to show that <m>u\ne \pm 1</m>. We have 
    <md>
        <mrow>u=\pm 1 \amp \implies \alpha\beta=\pm M </mrow>
        <mrow> \amp \implies \alpha\beta\overline{\beta}=\pm M\overline{\beta}</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp \implies \alpha\cdot M=\pm M \overline{\beta}</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp \implies \alpha=\pm \overline{\beta}</mrow>
    </md>.
    Since the last equality is excluded by our condition <m>m\ne \pm m'</m>, <m>n\ne\pm n'</m>, we see that <m>u\ne \pm 1</m>.
    </p>
    </case>
    
    </proof>
    </theorem>
    </subsection>
    <subsection xml:id="ss_neg_pells">
    <title>Negative Pell's equation</title>
    <p>
        Consider now the negative Pell's equation 
        <md>
            x^2-y^2d=-1
        </md>
        where <m>d&gt; 2</m> is a positive squarefree integer. Since <m>d</m> is squarefree, we have 
        <md>
            d=\prod_{i=1}^r p_i
        </md>
        for distinct primes <m>p_i</m>. If <m>(a,b)</m> is a solution in positive integers, then for all <m>1\leq i\leq r</m> we have 
        <md>
            <mrow>a^2-b^2d=-1 \amp \implies a^2\equiv -1 \pmod{p_i}  </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp \implies p_i\not\equiv 3\pmod 4</mrow>
        </md>,
        since as we have seen <m>\qr{-1}{p}=1</m> if and only if <m>p=2</m> or <m>p\equiv 1\pmod 4</m>. It follows that a <em>necessary condition</em> for the negative Pell's equation to have a solution is that no prime divisor of <m>d</m> is congruent to 3 modulo <m>4</m>. Interestingly, this is not in general a <em>sufficient condition</em>. The following <url href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/2201.13424">recent theorem by Koymans and Pagano</url>, building off of work by Northwestern's own Alex Smith, gives a precise quantitative description of just how far our necessary condition fails to be a sufficient one.
    </p>
        <theorem xml:id="th_neg_pells">
        <title>Negative Pell's equation
        </title>
        <creator>Koymans, Pagano, 2022</creator>
        
        <statement>
        <p>
        Let <m>D</m> be the set of all squarefree positive integers <m>d&gt; 1</m> whose prime divisors are congruent to <m>1</m> or <m>2</m> modulo <m>4</m>, and let <m>D^{-}</m> be the set of squarefree positive integers <m>d&gt; 1</m> for which the negative Pell's equation <m>x^2-dy^2=-1</m> has a solution. We have 
        <md number="yes">
            <mrow>\lim\limits_{N\to \infty} \frac{\abs{\{d\in D^{-}\mid d\leq N\}}}{\abs{\{d\in D\mid d\leq N\}}}\amp = 1-\prod_{j \text{ odd}}(1-1/2^j) </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp \approx 58\%</mrow>
        </md>.
        </p>
        </statement>
        </theorem>
        
        
    </p>
    </subsection>

</section>